\b \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q Do I need the Wii Console ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: No. You need the Wii Remote (a.k.a. Wiimote) and the Macintosh computer with Bluetooth. You also need the Sensor Bar (power-supplied by yourself) if you use IR-sensor. You can use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://ohmaccho.googlepages.com/self-producedsensorbar"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul \ulc3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 two IR-transmitters}} or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://akamatsu.org/aka/?p=99"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul \ulc3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 two candles}} instead of the Sensor Bar .\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: Can I use two Wiimotes ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: You can use multiple Wiimotes in 1.0B4 and later. I could connect five Wiimotes to one computer at a time. I have used {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://akamatsu.org/aka/?p=229"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul \ulc3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 eighteen Wiimotes}} with four computers.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: Does it support Nunchuk and Classic Controller ? 
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: Nunchuk is supported in 1.0B5. Classic Controller is supported in 1.0B6.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: The object is not created (dimmed).
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: Please note that you have to run it under the latest Mac OS X (10.4.8 and later) and Max (4.6.2 and later). The Bluetooth framework version should be 1.6.3 and later.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: I cannot connect the object to my Wiimote.
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: You have to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://akamatsu.org/aka/?p=121"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul \ulc3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 setup Wii Remote for use with your computer}} using [RVL Enabler] or [Bluetooth Setup Assistant] for the first time.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: Does it run on Intel-Mac and PowerPC-Mac ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: Yes. It is a universal binary Mach-O object. I checked it with my MacBook Pro and PowerBook G4, both with internal Bluetooth device. I also checked it with my PowerMac G5(2.5GHz/Quad) and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dlink.com/products/?pid=34"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul \ulc3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 D-Link DBT-120}} Bluetooth-USB Adapter.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: Is it buggy on PowerBook G4 ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: Sure. It is unstable and some functions does not work fine on PowerBook G4. In my experience, I had a good result if I do the following steps every time I use it on PowerBook G4. (You would set up only once on Intel-Mac.)\u8232 1: Delete \'93Nintendo RVL-CNT-01\'94 on \'93Device\'94 tab in \'93Bluetooth\'94 System Preference.\u8232 2: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://akamatsu.org/aka/?p=121"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul \ulc3 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Do the setup for Wii Remote}}.\uc0\u8232 3: Open \'93aka.wiiremote.help\'94 and connect it.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: Can I use the Wiimote that is sold outside Japan ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: Yes. I believe the Wiimotes are same in the world.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: What is the Sync button that is mentioned in the help patch ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: A small red button inside the Wiimote battery box. You can also push 1 and 2 buttons simultaneously to start the synchronization.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: The sound of vibration is a little unusual.
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: It was fixed in 1.0B3, I believe.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: Do you have the object for Windows and CFM ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: No. But I published my source code. So I hope someone would port it to them.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: Can I modify your source code and publish another version of the object ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: Yes. You can modify and publish it under the BSD license described in COPYRIGHT.txt in the distribution.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: What is the difference of DarwiinRemote and aka.wiiremote in source codes ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: I made it referring to the source code of WiiRemote Framework 0.4. But they are not same because of the difference of APIs and programming languages.\

\b \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 Q: What is the difference of DarwiinRemote and aka.wiiremote actually ?
\b0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \uc0\u8232 A: DarwiinRemote is an application software and aka.wiiremote is a Max object apparently. aka.wiiremote provides raw informations from Wiimote and has no practical function. Thus you would make your own patch by yourself.\
